Fair Speech Analysis

Interview data overview

There are 73 interviews with black speakers (from CORAAL), and 51 interviews with white speakers (from VOC). These audio snippets total 39.76 hours, pre-matching.

Propensity score matching

# Matching algorithm
set.seed(100)
mod_match <- matchit(black_flag ~ age_bin_35 + age_bin_45 + 
                       age_bin_55 + age_bin_65 + age_bin_75 + age_bin_85 + age_bin_95 +
                       age + female_flag + log_duration, 
                     method = "nearest", distance = 'logit', 
                     caliper = 0.001, data = reg_base)

dta_m <- match.data(mod_match)
matched_wer <- dta_m[,1:13]
write.csv(matched_wer, '../output/Matched_WER.csv', row.names = FALSE)

The resulting matching yields 2141 audio snippets from 73 black speakers, and 2141 audio snippets from 42 white speakers. These 4282 snippets, corresponding to 19.79 total hours of audio, are used for all ensuing analyses. Of these snippets, 44% have male speakers, average snippet duration is 17 seconds, and average speaker age is 45 years.

Confirming covariate balance

## Saving 12 x 7 in image

Average Word Error Rate by ASR Service

Across all ASRs, the average WER for transcriptions of black speakers is 0.35, nearly double the WER for white speakers 0.19. The maximum standard error across all ASRs and both races was 0.005.

Complementary CDF of Word Error Rates

Of the ASR transcriptions for white speakers’ snippets, only 1.6% of them had incomprensible WERs. Meanwhile, of transcriptions for black speakers, nearly ten times as many had incomprehensible WERs (22.7% with high WER).

Regressions separated by gender

As an example, for the average 45-year-old speaking for 30 seconds, Google’s ASR performs as follows:

  • Black man: WER = 0.37
  • Black woman: WER = 0.23
  • White man: WER = 0.19
  • White woman: WER = 0.14
